,"1300–1374":"1300–1374","1305–Female":"1305–Deceased","1325–1429":"1325–1429","1274–1313":"1274–1313","1279–1300":"1279–1300","1305":"1305","1325":"1325","1313":"1313","1279":"1279","1300":"1300","Abt 1298":"about 1298","About 1325":"about 1325","1298":"1298","1374":"1374","1274":"1274","1429":"1429","Warkworth, Northamptonshire, England":"Warkworth, Northamptonshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Saint","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Cyr, Remy.","English and French: nickname for a particularly pious individual, from Old French and Middle English <i>saint(e)</i>, <i>seint(e)</i> ‘holy’ (from Latin <i>sanctus</i> ‘blameless, holy’). The vocabulary word was occasionally used in the Middle Ages as a personal name and this may have given rise to some instances of the surname.","English: perhaps a nickname for someone who wore, made, or sold girdles, from Middle English <i>ceint</i>, <i>seint</i>, <i>saint</i> ‘girdle’ (Old French <i>ceint</i>, Latin <i>cinctum</i>). Compare   Center  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Center","meanings":["English and Scottish (Aberdeenshire): metonymic occupational name from Middle English, Old French <i>ceinture</i>, <i>seinture</i> ‘girdle’, denoting someone who made or sold girdles, or perhaps a nickname for someone who wore a distinctive girdle.","English: variant of   Senter   1.","Americanized form of German   Zehnder   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Sant","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Krishan, Anagha, Anjali, Arvind, Deepak, Milind, Nilima, Ravindra, Sanjeev, Sanjiv, Vasudev.","English (Cheshire and Staffordshire): variant of   Saint  .","Italian (northeastern): variant of   Santo  ."]},{"name":"Sante","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Luc, Camille, Lucien.  Spanish Alejandro, Anselmo, Carlos, Emilio, Jesusa, Jorge.","French (also <b>Santé</b>): probably a nickname for a healthy person, from French <i>santé</i> ‘good health’.","Galician, Asturian-Leonese, and Spanish (southwestern): habitational name from one of several places called Sante, in Galicia, Portugal, and Asturias, from a Visigothic personal name. This surname is also found in the Philippines."]}]},{"name":"Liz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Galician: habitational name from Liz in Lugo province, Galicia (Spain). As a Hispanic name it may also be an altered form of   Lis  . Compare   Deliz  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Stanislaw, Wladyslaw, Andrzej, Casimir, Ignatius, Malgorzata, Slawomir, Tadeusz, Tomasz, Boleslaw, Bronislaw, Darek.","Polish, Czech, Sorbian, and Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): from Polish and Czech dialect <i>lis</i> ‘fox’, Upper Sorbian <i>lis</i> ‘he-fox’, a nickname for a cunning person or, in the case of the Jewish name, an artificial name. The presumably cognate Sorbian surname <b>Liš</b> is found in Germanized and probably also Americanized forms, only (see   Liesch   and   Lish  ). Compare also   Lese  ,   Lies  , and   Liss  .","Czech: nickname for a man with a bald pate, from a variant of the adjective <i>lysý</i> ‘bald’."]}]},{"name":"Rowland","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roland  , or a transferred use of the surname derived from that given name in the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Roland","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. In Old French literature it is borne by a legendary Frankish hero, a vassal of Charlemagne, whose exploits are told in the <i>Chanson de Roland</i>. The subject of the poem is Roland's death at the Battle of Roncesvalles in the Pyrenees in  778 , while protecting the rearguard of the Frankish army on its retreat from Spain. Roland is depicted in literature and legend as headstrong and impulsive. His devoted friendship with the prudent  Oliver  is also legendary."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Rowland de Saint Liz was born about 1298, in England, United Kingdom, his father, William St Liz, was 26 and his mother, Anne, was 21. He had at least 1 son with Agnes Empingham."},"et":{"Abt 1298–":"umbes 1298–Surnud","1298–Male":"1298–Surnud","1300–1374":"1300–1374","1305–Female":"1305–Surnud","1325–1429":"1325–1429","1274–1313":"1274–1313","1279–1300":"1279–1300","1305":"1305","1325":"1325","1313":"1313","1279":"1279","1300":"1300","Abt 1298":"umbes 1298","About 1325":"umbes 1325","1298":"1298","1374":"1374","1274":"1274","1429":"1429","Warkworth, Northamptonshire, England":"Warkworth, Northamptonshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1298–":"noin 1298–Kuollut","1298–Male":"1298–Kuollut","1300–1374":"1300–1374","1305–Female":"1305–Kuollut","1325–1429":"1325–1429","1274–1313":"1274–1313","1279–1300":"1279–1300","1305":"1305","1325":"1325","1313":"1313","1279":"1279","1300":"1300","Abt 1298":"noin 1298","About 1325":"noin 1325",